http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/creator.@value: HL7 Security and CBCC Work Groups

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/descript.@value: This ontology currently represents core HL7 Security and Privacy concepts.

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/source.@value: HL7 Composite Security and Privacy Domain Analysis Model, May, 2010.
HL7 Healthcare Privacy and Security Classification System (HCS)
ISO/TS 21298: Health informatics — Functional and structural roles
ISO/TS 22600 Health informatics – Privilege management and access control, 2006.

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/descript.@value: An authority is an organization (either Jurisdictional or Provider) that is responsible for a Privacy Policy.

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/source.@value: HL7 Composite Security and Privacy DAM

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: According to the CSP-DAM: 'This abstract class is used to designate the authority that issues the policy.'

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/descript.@value: An authorization policy defines allowed actions.
A basic security policy serves as a common basis for more specific types of security policies, for example authorization, delegation, obligation and refrain policies.
A clearinghouse is an organization that collects, classifies and/or distributes (healthcare) information.

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/source.@value: HL7 Composite Security and Privacy DAM

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: Description derived from Merriam Webster.
Mentioned in text of CSP-DAM though not specified there as a class.

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/descript.@value: A client is a person who is the subject of a consent directive. [HL7 CSP-DAM]

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/source.@value: HL7 Composite Security and Privacy DAM

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: The definition of Client is debatable.  On the other hand, a client with no consent directive arguably has no impact on access control."

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/descript.@value: As a part of the service they provide to patients, medical doctors, nurses and allied health workers compile notes that document the conditions they encounter, the treatments provided and the outcomes of those treatments. [U.S. National Library of Medicine; http://www.nlm.nih.gov/nichsr/usestats/clinical_observation.html; Retrieved on July 29, 2013]

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/source.@value: HL7 HCS

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: ClinicalObservation is a generalization of the ClinicalCondition class from the HL7 CSP-DAM.
Subclasses of ClinicalObservation are specified in ClinicalObservationOntology.owl.

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/descript.@value: A compartment is a security label tag that "segments" an IT resource by indicating that access and use is restricted to members of a defined community or project.

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/source.@value: HL7 Healthcare Privacy and Security Classification System (HCS)

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/descript.@value: A composite security policy combines other policies (authorization, constraint, delegation, obligation, and/or refrain policies).
Confidentiality is the property that information is not made available or disclosed to unauthorized individuals. [per ISO 7498-2:1989]

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/source.@value: HL7 Composite Security and Privacy DAM, which cites ISO 7498-2:1989.

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: Subclasses of Confidentiality are specified in ConfidentialityOntology.owl.

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/descript.@value: A Consenter is a person who is an individual client of healthcare services or a client delegate (Substitute Decision Maker) that uses a computer system to manage client privacy consent directives.

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/source.@value: HL7 Composite Security and Privacy DAM

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/descript.@value: A constraint is a restriction (condition or obligation) that is enforced upon access permissions.

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/source.@value: ANSI/INCITS 359-2004

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: In the future, subclasses of Constraint may be moved to a separate sub-ontology.

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/descript.@value: A constraint catalog is a collection of constraints on permissions (as specified by an organization).

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/source.@value: HL7 RBAC Constraint Catalog

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/descript.@value: A constraint policy places constraints on another policy.

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/source.@value: HL7 Composite Security and Privacy DAM

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/descript.@value: The DataOperation class categorizes operations from the perspective of their effect on object(s).

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/source.@value: HL7 Composite Security and Privacy DAM

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: Subclasses of DataOperation are specified in CRUDEA_OperationOntology.owl and in turn in DataOperationOntology.owl.

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/descript.@value: A delegation policy defines what authorizations can be delegated to whom.
A functional role reflects functional aspects of relationships between entities. Functional roles are bound to the realization/performance of acts.

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: [taken from HL7 RBAC Role Engineering Process:] Functional Roles consist of all the permissions (operations on health information system objects) needed to perform a task.  Functional role names are associated with groups of permissions for convenience in assigning to users.

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/descript.@value: A grantee is a person or organization given privilege(s), e.g., by a delegation policy.

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/source.@value: HL7 Composite Security and Privacy DAM

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/descript.@value: A health record stores healthcare information about a person.

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/source.@value: HL7 Composite Security and Privacy DAM

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/descript.@value: An information reference is a specification of the attributes of protected information referenced by a policy.

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/source.@value: HL7 Composite Security and Privacy DAM

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/descript.@value: Integrity is the attribute that information is not altered in any way, deliberately or accidentally.

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: Made a meaningless change in the wording of the ISO definition, from 'property' to 'attribute' to avoid confusion with OWL properties.
Subclasses of Integrity are specified in IntegrityOntology.owl.

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/descript.@value: An interorganizational agreement specifies (security and privacy) arrangements among organizations.

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/source.@value: 'Refrain Policy Vocabulary' presentation to HL7 Security WG by Kathleen Connor in November 2011.

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/descript.@value: A jurisdiction is an area with a set of laws under the control of a system of courts which are different to neighboring areas.

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/source.@value: HL7 Composite Security and Privacy DAM

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: In the future, instances of Jurisdiction may be defined in a separate sub-ontology.  For now, sample instances  are included within SomewhereHospitalOntology.owl.

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/descript.@value: A jurisdictional organization is an organization that has territorial authority.

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/source.@value: HL7 Composite Security and Privacy DAM

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/descript.@value: A location is a site (such as a physical place or a system, workstation or terminal in a network).

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/source.@value: HL7 Composite Security and Privacy DAM

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: It is expected that specific organizations will create and maintain their own subclasses and instances of Location.
Should an Organization have a LocationSet to capture the locations which it may use in policies to control access?

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/descript.@value: An object is an entity that contains or receives information.  An object can represent information containers (e.g., files or directories in an operating system, and/or columns, rows, tables, and views within a database management system) or objects can represent exhaustible system resources, such as printers, disk space, and CPU cycles.

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/source.@value: HL7 RBAC (based on ANSI/INCITS 359-2004)

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: Subclasses of Object are specified in ObjectOntology.owl.

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/descript.@value: An obligation represents a resposibility to follow a course of action.

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/source.@value: HL7 Composite Security and Privacy DAM

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: Subclasses of Obligation are specified in ObligationOntology.owl.

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/descript.@value: An obligation policy is event-triggered and defines actions to be performed by manager agents.

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: ISO 22600-2 describes obligation policy in terms of manager agents but says nothing about the latter.

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/descript.@value: To operate is to act on an object or objects.  An operation is an executable image of a program, which upon invocation executes some function for the user.  Within a file system, operations might include read, write, and execute.  Within a database management system, operations might include append, delete, and update.

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/source.@value: HL7 Composite Security and Privacy DAM

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: For the Security and Privacy Ontology in general, we have adopted 'CamelCase' naming which differd slightly from the HL7 RBAC Permission Catalog and from the HL7 vocabulary repository (which also differ from each other).

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/descript.@value: An organization is an administrative and/or functional entity.

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/source.@value: HL7 Composite Security and Privacy DAM

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: In the Composite Security and Privacy DAM, a generalization of JurisdictionalOrganization and ProviderOrganization is named 'Authority'.  However, ISO 22600-2 defines Authority as 'entity that is responsible for the issuance of certificates'.

It is expected that specific organizations will create and maintain their own sub-ontology which imports SecurityAndPrivacyOntology.owl along with some or all of the accompanying subontologies and adds suitable local instances of classes.
Organization has exactly one role set per conversation with M. Davis et al., 08/24/2010.
Textual description derived from Merriam Webster.

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/descript.@value: A payment source is the provider of payment for the healthcare services documented by electronic health records.

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/source.@value: HL7 Composite Security and Privacy DAM

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: Subclasses of PaymentSource are specified in PaymentSourceOntology.owl.
The CSP-DAM names the class PolicyProgramPaymentSource but its decription is strictly in terms of payment.

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/descript.@value: A person is a human being.

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/source.@value: De novo

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: Obvious generalization of Client, Consenter and similar classes.

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/descript.@value: A policy is a set of legal, political, organizational, functional and technical obligations or omissions for communication and cooperation.  [ISO 22600-3]
A population is a subject of privacy policy or consent which is a body of persons or individuals having a quality or characteristic in common.

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/source.@value: HL7 Composite Security and Privacy DAM

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/descript.@value: A privacy consent directive is special policy which defines an agreement between an entity playing the role of the subject of an act and an entity acting. [ISO 22600-3]

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/source.@value: HL7 Composite Security and Privacy DAM

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: According to the CSP-DAM: 'A Privacy Consent Directive is defined as 'an instruction regarding consent and contextual conditions to collect, use, and/or disclose Personal Health Information.' This definition is adapted from the British Columbia, E-Health (Personal Health Information Access and Protection of Privacy) Act, S.B.C. 2008, c. 38, s. 1.'

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/descript.@value: The PrivacyOperation class categorizes operations from the perspective of their effect on the privacy of (health) information.

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/source.@value: HL7 Composite Security and Privacy DAM

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: Subclasses of PrivacyOperation are specified in PrivacyOperationOntology.owl.

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/descript.@value: A privacy policy is a policy that is concerned with information privacy practices.

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/source.@value: HL7 Composite Security and Privacy DAM

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/descript.@value: A privacy rule specifies permission or obligation to treat information in accord with privacy wishes.

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/source.@value: HL7 Composite Security and Privacy DAM

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/descript.@value: A provider organization is an organization that furnishes healthcare.

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/source.@value: HL7 Composite Security and Privacy DAM

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/descript.@value: A purpose of use is an intention for which an object is accessed.

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/source.@value: HL7 Composite Security and Privacy DAM

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: Subclasses of PurposeOfUse are specified in PurposeOfUseOntology.owl.

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/descript.@value: A refrain represents a responsibility to not follow a course of action.

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/source.@value: HL7 v3 RefrainPolicy value set.

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: Subclasses of Refrain are specified in RefrainOntology.owl.

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/descript.@value: A refrain policy is a policy used to indicate that a specific action is prohibited based on specific access control attributes (e.g., purpose of use, information type, user role, etc.).
A role set is a collection of roles (as specified by an organization).

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/source.@value: De novo

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/descript.@value: A route is a sequence of links, and/or partial links, that describe a path, usually between two positions, within a network [ISO 19133:2005] [ISO 19134:2007, 4.11]

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/source.@value: HL7 Composite Security and Privacy DAM

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: Subclasses of Route are specified in RouteOntology.owl.

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/descript.@value: A security policy is a policy that is concerned with information security practices.
A set of rules laid down by the security authority governing the use and provision of security services and facilities [ISO/TS 22600-3:2009(E)]
A set of rules that constrains one or more sets of activities of one or more sets of objects [ISO/IEC 10746-3]
plan or course of action adopted for providing computer security [ISO/TS 22600-1:2006(E), ISO/TS 22600-2:2006(E), and ISO/TS 22600-3:2009(E)]

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/source.@value: HL7 Composite Security and Privacy DAM

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: The Composite Security and Privacy DAM has a class named 'Policy' but refers in text to the more specific notion of 'Security Policy'.

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/descript.@value: A role is set of competences and/or performances that are associated with a task.

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/source.@value: ISO/TS 21298:2008(E) and ANSI/INCITS 359-2004

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: 'Role' is considered a synonym for this 'SecurityRole' class per the 08/24/2010 meeting of the Security WG.
Roles provide a means of indirectly assigning privileges to individuals.
Subclasses of SecurityRole are specified in RoleOntology.owl.

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/descript.@value: Sensitivity specifies the characteristic of a resource which implies its value or importance, and may include its vulnerability [ISO 7498-2:1989]. Vulnerability here is defined as medically vulnerable with respect to privacy, subject to social stigmatization.

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: Subclasses of Sensitivity are specified in SensitivityOntology.owl.

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/descript.@value: A separation of duty constraint is a constraint that defines exclusivity relations among roles.

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/source.@value: ANSI/INCITS 359-2004

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/descript.@value: A role of a place that further classifies the setting (e.g., accident site, road side, work site, community location) in which services are delivered.

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/source.@value: HL7 v3 ServiceDeliveryLocationRoleType value set

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: Subclasses of ServiceDeliveryLocation are specified in ServiceDeliveryLocationOntology.owl.

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/descript.@value: A structural role reflects the structural aspects of relationships between entities.  Structural roles describe prerequisites, feasibilities or competences for acts.

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: According to the HL7 CSP-DAM: A structural role is a security role that places a user in an organizational hierarchy as belonging to a category of healthcare personnel warranting certain levels of access control: Structural roles allow users to participate in the organization’s workflow (e.g., tasks) by job, title, or position, but do not specify detailed permissions on specific information objects.  Structural roles allow a user to “connect” to a resource, but do not grant authorizations.

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/descript.@value: A subject of [a] record is a person or population described by a health record (record object).

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/source.@value: HL7 Composite Security and Privacy DAM

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/descript.@value: A user assignment is an association of a user with role(s) he or she is allowed to assume.

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/source.@value: ANSI/INCITS 359-2004

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: It is expected that specific organizations will create and maintain their own instances of UserAssignment.

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/descript.@value: A user assignment set is a collection of assignments of users to roles (as specified by an organization).

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/source.@value: De novo

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/descript.@value: A user identity is the representation of a human being in an information system.

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/source.@value: HL7 Composite Security and Privacy DAM

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/descript.@value: Describes role(s) subject to assignment.
Describes user(s) subject to assignment.

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: May eliminate this specialization of the authorizedBy property.
May eliminate this specialization of the authorizedBy property.
May eliminate this specialization of the authorizedBy property.
May eliminate this specialization of the authorizedBy property.

Relates a constraint policy to a policy it constrains.
Describes exercise of control over a type of information reference.
Exercises control over a type of operation.
Describes exercise of control for a purpose.
Describes exercise of control over a type of role.
Describes constraint catalog(s) posessed.

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: Intended to capture the web location where the document in question is published for human consumption, as opposed to the URI of this ontology element.

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/descript.@value: Describes set(s) of roles posessed.
Describes user assignment(s) posessed.
Describes role(s) included within a set.
Describes user assignment(s) included within a set.
Describes input object(s) operated on.
Describes input-output object(s) operated on.
Describes object(s) operated on.
Describes output object(s) operated on.
